[[File:Kouka jinja2009-6.jpg|thumb|right|220px|Statue of "Takamitsu-kō and Sarutorahebi" at {{ill|Kōka Shrine (Seki)|ja|高賀神社|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Seki, Gifu|ja|関市|qq=draft}}]] [[File:Mount Koga from Kouka jinja (2015-01-24).JPG|right|thumb|220px|Torii gate of Kōka Shrine with {{ill|Mount Kōga|ja|高賀山|qq=draft}} in the background]]
'''{{ill|Kinpu Shrine (Mino)|ja|金峰神社|qq=draft}}''' (かねみねじんじゃ<ref>{{Cite web|title=Kinpu Shrine - Gifu Prefecture Shrine Association|url=https://www.gifu-jinjacho.jp/syosai.php?shrno=2481|accessdate=2022-10-30}}</ref>) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|qq=draft}} located in {{ill|Mino, Gifu|ja|美濃市|qq=draft}}, Japan. It is one of the six shrines that form the core of **{{ill|Mount Kōga faith|ja|高賀山信仰|qq=draft}}** (高賀山六社).
== Overview == The shrine is one of the **{{ill|Six Shrines of Mount Kōga|ja|高賀山六社|qq=draft}}**, located along the {{ill|Katachi River|ja|片知川|qq=draft}}, a tributary of the {{ill|Itadori River|ja|板取川|qq=draft}}, itself a tributary of the {{ill|Nagara River|ja|長良川|qq=draft}}.
Locals commonly refer to the shrine as "Kanemine Jinja" (かねみねじんじゃ).
== Enshrined Deity == * {{ill|Zaō Gongen|ja|蔵王権現|qq=draft}}
The actual sacred objects of worship are said to be statues of: * {{ill|Amitābha|ja|阿弥陀如来|qq=draft}} * {{ill|Ekādaśamukha|ja|十一面観世音菩薩|qq=draft}} * {{ill|Kṣitigarbha|ja|地蔵菩薩|qq=draft}}
Additionally, flanking these statues are images of {{ill|Kongō Zaō|ja|金剛蔵王|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Tenbu|ja|天部|qq=draft}} deities.
== History == According to shrine tradition, during the **Tenryaku era** (947–957), the **Sarutorahebi** (さるとらへび), a mythical yokai, began terrorizing the local villages. The {{ill|Imperial Court (Japan)|ja|朝廷|qq=draft}} dispatched {{ill|Fujiwara no Takamitsu|ja|藤原高光|qq=draft}} to exterminate it.<ref>Another theory suggests the event took place in **Shōhei 3** (933), but this conflicts with Fujiwara no Takamitsu's birth year.</ref>
The first sighting of the Sarutorahebi was at this location, leading to the naming of the area **"Katachi"** (形知), now known as **Katachi** (片知). A shrine was then built in commemoration of the event, originally known as **Katachi Shrine**.
Over time, {{ill|Mount Kōga|ja|高賀山|qq=draft}} gained reverence as a sacred site in {{ill|Mino Province|ja|美濃国|qq=draft}}. Influenced by {{ill|Shugendō|ja|修験道|qq=draft}}, the shrine was later renamed **Zaō Gongen Shrine** (蔵王権現社). During the early **Meiji period**, it was renamed **Kinpu Shrine** (金峰神社), likely in reference to {{ill|Kinpusen-ji|ja|金峯山寺|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Yoshino, Nara|ja|吉野町|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Nara Prefecture|ja|奈良県|qq=draft}}.
== The Six Shrines of Mount Kōga == The **Six Shrines of Mount Kōga** are located around Mount Kōga (高賀山), {{ill|Mount Hyōga|ja|瓢ケ岳|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Mount Imabuchi|ja|今渕ケ岳|qq=draft}}, and {{ill|Mount Katachi|ja|片知山|qq=draft}}. Traditionally, ascetics would complete a **one-day pilgrimage** known as **Six Shrine Pilgrimage** (六社めぐり), trekking across mountain ridges.
The six shrines are: * {{ill|Kōka Shrine (Seki)|ja|高賀神社|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Seki, Gifu|ja|関市|qq=draft}}) * {{ill|Nabi Shingū Shrine|ja|那比新宮神社|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Gujo, Gifu|ja|郡上市|qq=draft}}) * {{ill|Nabi Hongū Shrine|ja|本宮神社 (郡上市)|qq=draft}} (Gujo, Gifu) * {{ill|Hoshimiya Shrine|ja|星宮神社 (郡上市)|qq=draft}} (Gujo, Gifu) * {{ill|Taki Shrine (Mino)|ja|瀧神社|qq=draft}} (Mino, Gifu) * **Kinpu Shrine** (Mino, Gifu)
== Access == * **By Bus:** {{ill|Gifu Bus|ja|岐阜乗合自動車|qq=draft}} **Makidani Line** – Get off at **Kanemonbashi (金門橋) Bus Stop**.
== References == {{Reflist}}
== External Links == * [https://www.gifu-jinjacho.jp/ Gifu Prefecture Shrine Association] (岐阜県神社庁)
