The actual sacred objects of worship are said to be statues of: * {{ill|Amitābha|ja|阿弥陀如来|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Amitābha|qq=}} * {{ill|Ekādaśamukha|ja|十一面観世音菩薩|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ekādaśamukha|qq=}} * {{ill|Kṣitigarbha|ja|地蔵菩薩|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kṣitigarbha|qq=}}
Additionally, flanking these statues are images of {{ill|Kongō Zaō|ja|金剛蔵王|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kongō Zaō|qq=}} and {{ill|Tenbu|ja|天部|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenbu|qq=}} deities.
== History == According to shrine tradition, during the **Tenryaku era** (947–957), the **Sarutorahebi** (さるとらへび), a mythical yokai, began terrorizing the local villages. The {{ill|Imperial Court (Japan)|ja|朝廷|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Imperial Court (Japan)|qq=}} dispatched {{ill|Fujiwara no Takamitsu|ja|藤原高光|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fujiwara no Takamitsu|qq=}} to exterminate it.<ref>Another theory suggests the event took place in **Shōhei 3** (933), but this conflicts with Fujiwara no Takamitsu's birth year.</ref>
The first sighting of the Sarutorahebi was at this location, leading to the naming of the area **"Katachi"** (形知), now known as **Katachi** (片知). A shrine was then built in commemoration of the event, originally known as **Katachi Shrine**.
Over time, {{ill|Mount Kōga|ja|高賀山|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mount Kōga|qq=}} gained reverence as a sacred site in {{ill|Mino Province|ja|美濃国|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mino Province|qq=}}. Influenced by {{ill|Shugendō|ja|修験道|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shugendō|qq=}}, the shrine was later renamed **Zaō Gongen Shrine** (蔵王権現社). During the early **Meiji period**, it was renamed **Kinpu Shrine** (金峰神社), likely in reference to {{ill|Kinpusen-ji|ja|金峯山寺|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kinpusen-ji|qq=}} in {{ill|Yoshino, Nara|ja|吉野町|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yoshino, Nara|qq=}}, {{ill|Nara Prefecture|ja|奈良県|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nara Prefecture|qq=}}.
== The Six Shrines of Mount Kōga == The **Six Shrines of Mount Kōga** are located around Mount Kōga (高賀山), {{ill|Mount Hyōga|ja|瓢ケ岳|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mount Hyōga|qq=}}, {{ill|Mount Imabuchi|ja|今渕ケ岳|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mount Imabuchi|qq=}}, and {{ill|Mount Katachi|ja|片知山|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mount Katachi|qq=}}. Traditionally, ascetics would complete a **one-day pilgrimage** known as **Six Shrine Pilgrimage** (六社めぐり), trekking across mountain ridges.
The six shrines are: * {{ill|Kōka Shrine (Seki)|ja|高賀神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kōka Shrine (Seki)|qq=}} ({{ill|Seki, Gifu|ja|関市|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Seki, Gifu|qq=}}) * {{ill|Nabi Shingū Shrine|ja|那比新宮神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nabi Shingū Shrine|qq=}} ({{ill|Gujo, Gifu|ja|郡上市|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gujo, Gifu|qq=}}) * {{ill|Nabi Hongū Shrine|ja|本宮神社 (郡上市)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nabi Hongū Shrine|qq=}} (Gujo, Gifu) * {{ill|Hoshimiya Shrine|ja|星宮神社 (郡上市)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hoshimiya Shrine|qq=}} (Gujo, Gifu) * {{ill|Taki Shrine (Mino)|ja|瀧神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Taki Shrine (Mino)|qq=}} (Mino, Gifu) * **Kinpu Shrine** (Mino, Gifu)
